          "body": "Immediately before the Redeemer confession, Job wishes his words could be inscribed permanently — in a book, with iron stylus and lead poured into the incisions, engraved in rock forever. In the ancient Near East, such permanent inscription was reserved for royal decrees, treaty oaths, and temple dedications — documents that were meant to outlast the people who wrote them. Job wants his testimony to survive him, because no living witness will defend him. The pathos of verses 23-24 is that Job is reaching for the most permanent technology available to him and still finding it insufficient. Stone can be defaced, lead can be melted, books can be burned. What he actually needs — as verse 25 immediately demonstrates — is not a record in stone but a Redeemer who lives. The wish for inscription gives way at once to the confession of the living goel: what no scribe can guarantee, the living Redeemer secures."
