          "title": "Warning — the friends' pursuit will meet judgment (19:28-29)",
          "body": "The chapter's closing verses are often underread but are structurally necessary. Having made the most confident affirmation in the book, Job turns back to the friends with a warning. If they ask 'how shall we persecute him?' and seek a pretext for a case against him, let them fear the sword — 'for wrath brings the punishment of the sword, so that you may know there is judgment (din).' The word din in verse 29 is a legal verdict, a judicial decision. This is Job the plaintiff speaking: the same God whom Job has accused of wronging him (19:6) and whose justice he cannot currently find (19:7) is the God who will judge those who persecute the innocent. The argument of the chapter is completed: Job is not simply venting. He is operating with a coherent theology in which the present silence of justice and the future certainty of judgment coexist. The Redeemer who will stand on the earth (19:25) is the same God who will bring judgment (19:29). The friends, by persecuting Job, have placed themselves on the wrong side of the case the living Redeemer will adjudicate."
